    <h1>Role of Jenkins in CI/CD</h1>

    <div class="highlight">
      Jenkins is an open-source automation server widely used to implement 
      <b>Continuous Integration (CI)</b> and <b>Continuous Deployment/Delivery (CD)</b>.
    </div>

    <h2>ðŸ”¹ Key Uses:</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><b>Automation of Build & Testing:</b> Builds source code and runs tests automatically.</li>
      <li><b>Continuous Integration:</b> Integrates code frequently from developers and detects issues early.</li>
      <li><b>Continuous Deployment:</b> Deploys applications to staging or production environments.</li>
      <li><b>Pipeline as Code:</b> Uses <code>Jenkinsfile</code> to define CI/CD pipelines.</li>
      <li><b>Plugins Support:</b> Integrates with Git, Maven, Docker, Kubernetes, SonarQube, etc.</li>
      <li><b>Cross-Platform & Scalable:</b> Runs on Linux, Windows, Mac with distributed builds.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>âœ… In Simple Words:</h2>
    <p>
      Jenkins acts as the <b>automation engine</b> in CI/CD pipelines.  
      It <i>fetches code â†’ builds â†’ tests â†’ deploys â†’ monitors</i>,  
      making software delivery faster, reliable, and efficient.
